{{Speciesbox | name = Desert dormouse | fossil_range = Recent | image = Selevinia betpakdalaensis.jpg | status = DD | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{IUCN2008|assessor=Tsytsulina, K. |year=2008|id=20102|title=Selevinia betpakdalaensis|downloaded=3 August 2016}}</ref> | display_parents = 2 | genus = Selevinia | parent_authority = Belosludov & Bazhanov, 1939 | species = betpakdalaensis | authority = Belosludov & Bazhanov, 1939 }}
The '''desert dormouse''' (''Selevinia betpakdalaensis'') is a species of [[rodent]] in the [[dormouse]] [[family (biology)|family]], [[Gliridae]]. This species was formerly placed in its own family, '''Seleviniidae''', but it is now considered to be a dormouse, [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic]] within the genus '''''Selevinia'''''.<ref name = MSW3>{{MSW3 Gliridae | id = 12500039 | pages = 838 | heading = Family Gliridae}}</ref> It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Kazakhstan]].
==Taxonomy== The desert dormouse was [[Species description|first described]] in 1939 by Belosludov & Bazhanov as ''Selevinia betpakdalaensis'', the specific name being derived from the [[Betpak-Dala |Betpak-Dala Desert]], west of [[Lake Balkhash]] in [[Kazakhstan]], where the [[Type (biology)|type specimen]] was found. They included it in the rat and mouse [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Muridae]] but later proposed placing it in a new family allied to [[Myoxidae]] (some taxonomists call this family Gliridae), the dormice. By 1947, they had concluded that it should be placed in [[Leithiinae]], a subfamily of Myoxidae, along with three other dormouse genera.<ref name=Rafferty>{{cite book|author=Rafferty, John P.|title=Rats, Bats, and Xenarthrans|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Qm86amYgDfMC&pg=PA68 |year=2011 |publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|isbn=978-1-61530-332-8|pages=68–69}}</ref>
==Description== This dormouse has a head-and-body length of between {{convert|75|and|95|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} and a tail of between {{convert|58|and|77|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}. It has a robust, rounded body and soft dense fur, the upper parts being grey and the underparts white. Unusually for a mammal, it sheds the upper layers of its skin with the hairs when it moults, starting at the back of the neck and continuing along the body and flanks, the whole process taking about a month. The tail is well clad with short hairs and the soles of the feet are naked.<ref name=EDGE>{{cite web |url=http://www.edgeofexistence.org/mammals/species_info.php?id=60 |title=Desert Dormouse (''Selevinia betpakdalaensis'') |publisher=EDGE |accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> The upper incisors are large but the cheek teeth are small and barely project through the gums.<ref name=Rafferty/>
==Ecology== The species lives in sandy or clayey soils in arid habitats.<ref>{{cite book|author=Feldhamer, George A.|title=Mammalogy: Adaptation, Diversity, Ecology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=udCnKce9hfoC&pg=PA359 |year=2007 |publisher=JHU Press|isbn=978-0-8018-8695-9 |page=359}}</ref> It is mainly a [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]] animal but does sometimes venture into the open during the day. It mostly walks along in a leisurely fashion but if alarmed, can move faster in a series of short bounds. It lives among desert shrubs such as ''[[Artemisia maritima]]'' and ''[[Salsola laricifolia ]]'' and can climb efficiently. These animals have been little studied in the wild, but in captivity may shelter under rocks and foliage when the weather is warm and only burrow underground during cold periods. It mostly feeds on insects and spiders, but has been known to consume vegetation.<ref name=Rafferty/> It [[Hibernation|hibernates]] during the coldest months of the year, only being active between about March and September.<ref name=iucn/> Pregnant and lactating females have been found in late May and June, with litter sizes of four to eight young being recorded.<ref name=iucn/>
==Status== ''S. betpakdalaensis'' has a large range in Kazakhstan but is not abundant, being known from only about forty individuals scattered over about thirty locations. The total population and its trend are unknown and it may be threatened by the loss of the desert shrubs among which it lives. Because of these uncertainties, the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] has assessed its conservation status as "[[data deficient]]".<ref name=iucn/>
