'''''Growing Up Female: A Personal Photo-Journal''''' (1974) was a "landmark"<ref name="transom">[http://transom.org/?page_id=6436 transom.org]</ref> book of photography by photojournalist [[Abigail Heyman]] (1942-2013).<ref name="nytobit">Paul Vitello, [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/06/09/arts/design/abigail-heyman-feminist-photojournalist-dies-at-70.html "Abigail Heyman, Feminist Photojournalist, Dies at 70"] (obituary), ''[[New York Times]]'', June 9, 2013.</ref><ref name="pdnobit">[[Holly Stuart Hughes]], [http://www.pdnonline.com/news/Obituary-Photojourn-8317.shtml "Obituary: Photojournalist Abigail Heyman, Documenter of Women’s Changing Roles, 70"], ''Photo District News'', June 10, 2013.</ref>
Heyman introduced the book, writing "This book is about women, and their lives as women, from one feminist’s point of view."<ref name="pdnobit" /> The book collected photographs of Heyman's life, "challeng[ing] assumptions about being a woman", and "documented the female experience from a feminist perspective."<ref name="transom" /> [[Andy Grundberg]] described the book as "test[ing] the line between reportage and personal expression."<ref>Cited in ''Transom''; {{citation needed|date=June 2013}}</ref> The book portrayed numerous black-and-white images of women in various activities, including a photograph of Ms. Heyman herself having an abortion.<ref name="nytobit" />
During the 1970s, the work sold more than 35,000 copies, and was a mainstay of [[women's bookstores]] and [[feminist literature]] displays, along with ''[[Our Bodies, Ourselves]]''.<ref name="nytobit" />
