[[File:Amalthea (Voyager 1).png|thumb|170px|right|Amalthea (photo by ''[[Voyager 1]]''). Ida Facula is an upper bright spot]] '''Ida Facula''' is a bright [[mountain]] on [[Amalthea (moon)|Amalthea]], one of [[Jupiter]]'s smallest moons. It is known to be about 15 kilometers in width, somewhat smaller than the neighboring mountain [[Lyctos Facula]].<ref name="Thomas Burns et al. 1998" /> It was discovered by ''[[Voyager 1]]'' in 1979 and in the same year named for [[Mount Ida]], a mountain in [[Crete]] where [[Zeus]] played as a child.<ref name="USGS: Jupiter: Amalthea: Ida Facula" /> Firstly it was called simply ''Ida''.<ref name="Thomas Burns et al. 1998"/><ref name=Ververka_1981/>
